igh rate of deaths in the fishing industry. The book makes a unique contribution to understanding human-environment relations, examining the places fishers create and name at sea, as well as technologies and navigation practices. It combines phenomenology and political economy to offer new approaches for analyses of human-environment relations and technologies.This book is relevant to United Nations Sustainable Development Goal 14, Life below water  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFisheriesxEconomic aspectszScotland. 0aFisheriesxEnvironmental aspectszScotland. 0aFisheriesxSocial aspectszScotland. 0aFishery policyzScotland. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aLife below water.  aMarxist approach.  acapitalism.  adecolonised anthropology.  adigital GPS plotters.  afishing industry.  ahuman-environment relations.  ahuman-machine relation.  alabour at sea.  amaintenance.  anavigation devices.  apolitical economy.  asafe seamanship.  aviolence.  awooden boats.1 aMcCall Howard, Penny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611456340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526114563423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526114563/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles